SECION 3.8.1

Exercise 3.8.1-#1 The plot has no correlation in terms of the data. Cty and hwy are to be correlate to other variables such as drv, class, ect.. In ohter only one of the reponse variables (cty or hwy) plotted on axis.

Many data points overlap. We can use geom_jitter to jitter the points by adding some noise.

Exercise 3.8.1-#2 The parameters to geom_jitter() that control the amount of jitter are width and height.

Exercise 3.8.1-#3 (Part 1)

ggplot(data=mpg, mapping=aes(x=cty, y=hwy))+
  geom_jitter()

Exercise 3.8.1-#3 (Part 2)

ggplot(data=mpg, mapping=aes(x=cty, y=hwy))+
  geom_count()

While geom_jitter adds noise, geom_count counts the number of observations at each location and maps the count to point area. The points are being made larger when there are more observations in that area.

Exercise 3.8.1-#4 The default position adjustments is position_dodge().

ggplot(data=mpg, mapping=aes(x=class, y=hwy, color=drv))+
  geom_boxplot(position="dodge")

Exercise 5.2.4-#4 NA^0 equals 1 because anything to the power of 0 is 1.

With NA | TRUE, since the | operator returns TRUE if either of the terms are true, the whole expression returns true because the right half returns true.

& returns TRUE when both terms are true. So, for example, TRUE & TRUE evaluates to TRUE. In FALSE & NA, one of the terms is false, so the expression evaluates to FALSE.

One expect that NA times 0 should give 0, but the result is NA. The reason is because NA could be either a finite or infinity (Inf) number. When NA is finite we get 0. When NA is inf we get NaN. So we are facing with the two possible outcomes (0 or NaN) in NA*0. Since we dont which outcome we get, we say we dont know which is NA.
